/*Phase 1: Node.js — Production Patterns (Beginner-commented version)
1.1 — process & Environment Variables
Why this exists: In real jobs, your DB password / API keys / ports 
differ between your laptop, your teammate's laptop, and the live server.
 Hardcoding them means leaking secrets on GitHub (companies actually get hacked this
 way) and breaking the app every time the environment changes. .env solves this — one 
 file, never committed, holds all "secret config."
*/
// STEP 1: install dotenv (industry standard for loading .env files)
// run in terminal: npm install dotenv

// STEP 2: create a file named ".env" in your root folder (NOT .env.js, just ".env")
// .env
PORT = 5000
APP_NAME=MyFirstBackend
DB_URL=mongodb://localhost:27017/mydb

// process.env is a global object Node gives you, containing OS + your env variables

console.log('process.env.PORT');
console.log('process.env.APP_NAME');
console.log('process.env.DB_URL');

// process.argv = array of command-line arguments passed when you ran the file
console.log('process.argv');

console.log(process.platform); // 'win32' / 'linux' / 'darwin' -> useful for OS-specific logic
console.log(process.version);  // 'v22.x.x' -> which Node version is running this